The paper deals with a sorting algorithm, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and falls under the category of data structures (cs.DS). The use of empirical entropy suggests that the paper may also be relevant to information theory (cs.IT). The algorithm's performance is measured in terms of the number of comparisons, which is a common metric in computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper's focus on entropy and distinct elements suggests that it may also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the use of higher-order entropies and the algorithm's theoretical analysis may also make it relevant to machine learning and statistics (cs.LG).
